{"id": 12, "ts": 1779040496.033469, "event": "public_discussion_message", "round": 1, "agent": "agent_3", "message": "I provisionally favor **Candidate\u202fC** for the long\u2011distance pilot role.\n**Key evidence supporting C:**\n- 100\u202f% reliability and a strong sense of responsibility (explicitly noted).\n- Puts concern for others above everything and creates a positive crew atmosphere, indicating good crew\u2011centric attitude.\n- Excellent attention skills and the ability to make correct decisions quickly, which are vital for long\u2011haul operations.\n**Major alternatives and trade\u2011offs:**\n- **Candidate\u202fB** excels in stress handling, weather assessment, and technical (computer) skills, but is described as pretentious, sometimes uses the wrong tone, and makes nasty remarks about colleagues \u2013 serious red flags for teamwork and communication.\n- **Candidate\u202fA** shows strong technical cognition (danger anticipation, complex\u2011connection insight, spatial vision) and good leadership, yet is unfriendly and has an unhealthy diet, both of which could impair crew cohesion and long\u2011term health.\n- **Candidate\u202fD** demonstrates excellent problem\u2011solving, concentration, and responsibility, but is moody, regarded as a loner, and has weak leadership; no information on teamwork or communication is available, making the risk unclear.\n**Remaining uncertainties:**\n- I have no explicit data on Candidate\u202fC\u2019s technical competence in navigation, weather assessment, or other piloting\u2011specific skills.\n- The impact of C\u2019s difficulty communicating ideas and egocentric reputation on actual crew interaction is unclear.\n**What would change my vote:**\n- Evidence that C possesses strong technical piloting skills (navigation, meteorology) would solidify the choice.\n- Conversely, concrete examples of C\u2019s communication problems causing crew friction would shift preference toward another candidate (likely B, if his inte